span.p:
TProgramming paradigms,
languages, design patterns,
data structures, architecture,
algorithms, and their
practical implementations
across different programming
languages with idiomatic
specific examples

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Object-Oriented Programming
(OOP) concepts (encapsulation,
inheritance, polymorphism) and
their implementation in
languages like Java, Python,
and C++

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Functional Programming (FP)
concepts (immutability, pure
functions, higher-order
functions) and their
application in languages like
Haskell, Scala, and JavaScript

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Common Data Structures
(arrays, linked lists, trees,
graphs, hash tables) and their
performance characteristics

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Encapsulation: Bundling data
(attributes) and methods that
operate on the data within a
single unit (class) and
controlling access to the data

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Inheritance: Mechanism where a
new class (subclass or derived
class) inherits properties and
behaviors from an existing
class (superclass or base
class)

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Polymorphism: Ability of an
object to take on many forms,
allowing methods to perform
different actions based on the
object they are acting upon

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Immutability: Data that cannot
be changed after it is
created, promoting predictable
state and easier reasoning
about code.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Pure Functions: Functions that
always produce the same output
for the same input and have no
side effects.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Higher-Order Functions:
Functions that can take other
functions as arguments or
return functions as results.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Arrays: Contiguous blocks of
memory storing elements of the
same data type, offering
constant-time access by index.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Linked Lists: Sequential data
structures where elements are
linked using pointers,
allowing efficient insertion
and deletion but slower
access.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;

span.p:
Trees: Hierarchical data
structures with a root node
and child nodes, used for
efficient searching, sorting,
and hierarchical
representation.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Single Inheritance: A subclass
inherits from only one base
class.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;

span.p:
Multiple Inheritance: A
subclass inherits from more
than one base class.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Method Overriding: A subclass
provides a specific
implementation of a method
that is already defined in its
superclass.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Method Overloading: Defining
multiple methods with the same
name but different parameter
lists within the same class.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Abstract Classes and Methods:
Defining a base class that
cannot be instantiated and
abstract methods that must be
implemented by subclasses.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Interfaces: Contracts that
define a set of methods that a
class must implement, enabling
a form of polymorphism.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;

span.p:
Benefits of Immutability:
Reduced bugs, easier
concurrency, and improved
predictability.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Techniques for achieving
immutability in programming
languages (e.g., using `final`
in Java, `const` in
JavaScript, or specific
libraries).

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Immutability vs. Mutability:
Understanding the trade-offs
and when to use each.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Function as a First-Class
Citizen: Treating functions
like any other variable,
allowing them to be assigned,
passed as arguments, and
returned from other functions.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Common Higher-Order Functions:
Examples like `map`, `filter`,
and `reduce` and their
applications in data
manipulation.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;

span.p:
Currying and Partial
Application: Techniques for
transforming functions with
multiple arguments into a
sequence of functions each
taking a single argument.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Array Operations: Common
operations performed on arrays
such as insertion, deletion,
searching, and traversal,
along with their time
complexities.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Multidimensional Arrays:
Arrays with more than one
dimension, used to represent
matrices, tables, and other
grid-like data structures.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Dynamic Arrays (Lists): Data
structures that can resize
themselves automatically when
elements are added or removed,
offering flexibility over
fixed-size arrays.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Singly Linked Lists: Each node
contains data and a pointer to
the next node in the sequence.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Doubly Linked Lists: Each node
contains data and pointers to
both the next and previous
nodes in the sequence.

div.style: display: table-cell; white-space: nowrap; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center;

span.p:
Circular Linked Lists: The
last node's pointer points
back to the first node,
forming a loop.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Binary Trees: Trees where each
node has at most two children,
referred to as the left child
and the right child.

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Tree Traversal Algorithms:
Methods for visiting each node
in a tree exactly once (e.g.,
inorder, preorder, postorder,
level-order).

div.style: display: table; white-space: break-spaces; line-height: 1.5; max-width: 200px; text-align: center; width: 200px;

span.p:
Binary Search Trees (BSTs):
Binary trees where the left
subtree of a node contains
only nodes with keys lesser
than the node's key, and the
right subtree contains only
nodes with keys greater than
the node's key.
